[3]
Date: Tue, 24 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: MeatNews.Com Online, 12 Jun 2003 [edited]
Germany Beating BSE
--------------------
Germany's measures to control and beat BSE are having a positive effect.
Consumer minister Dr Gerald Thalheim told a recent farmers' union
meeting in Regensburg that the measures were minimising the risk from
BSE and ensuring consumer safety. The measures are also helping to
restore consumer confidence in beef and winning them back to a safe
and high quality product.
Dr Thalheim said that the most important measure that had been taken
was the ban on meat and bone meal in feed. He added that the testing
for BSE had brought more security, which was helped by the removal of
all specified risk material from the food chain and by stepping up
controls and sanctions on feedstuffs.
He said the federal government had also made Euro 13.8 million a year
available for research.
The number of cases of BSE in Germany is also staring to fall. In
2000, 7 cases were discovered, in 2001 there were 125 cases and last
year 106.
Dr Thalheim said that most of the cases had been found through the
monitoring system and the rapid BSE tests. A third of the cases had
been found through the tests after slaughter.
He added that in Germany they also tested all animals slaughtered
over the age of 24 months, where the European regulation was to test
animals over the age of 30 months.
He said that it was necessary to develop new tests to try to trace
BSE in younger animals and in animals while they were alive. And he
said that the Government was also evaluating the results of testing
animals over 24 months to assess whether it should continue with the
rapid tests in this form.
