[5]
Date: Tue, 24 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: calgary.cbc.ca, 24 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://calgary.cbc.ca/regional/servlet/View?filename=ca_klein20030624>
Klein hopes U.S. will "love Alberta beef"
-----------------------------------------
WASHINGTON: Premier Ralph Klein begins his mad cow mission in the
U.S. Tuesday, armed with "I love Alberta beef" T-shirts and a hard
sell about the safety of Canadian meat.
Klein, along with Saskatchewan Industry Minister Eric Cline, is to
hold talks with U.S. agriculture officials, before meeting with
Vice-President Dick Cheney on Wednesday. Klein has a friendship with
Cheney.
The U.S. border has been closed to Canadian beef since 20 May 2003
when a single cow was found to have bovine spongiform encephalopathy
(BSE). More than 2700 other cattle with a connection to the diseased
animal or its feed have been tested and didn't have BSE.
An international panel which reviewed the Canadian investigation and
called it "thorough" is expected to release its final report any day
now. The panel is staffed with experts from the U.S., Switzerland and
New Zealand.
Klein says the message he'll be delivering to the Americans is simple.
"There is absolutely no danger," he said. "The possibility of
catching that disease is one in 10 billion, billion meals."
The lieutenant governor of Montana says the U.S. would be unwise to
open the border before other countries are ready to accept Canadian
beef.
Karl Ohs met with Minister of Intergovernmental Relations Halvar
Jonson Monday and said there's a danger other countries would start
rejecting American as well as Canadian beef.
"I think you have to get all the trading partners  Japan, Korea, all
of those who buy North American beef  and they have to be satisfied
with where we're headed," Ohs said.
But Ohs said it's in his state's best interest to re-open the border
sooner rather than later.
"We're anxious to get normal trade moving again," he said, adding he
will make his position known to the U.S. government. "The longer this
goes on, the more volatile the beef industry in North America is."
Japan is already worried about Canadian beef finding its way overseas
through American exports. The Japanese have asked the U.S. to process
any Canadian-born cattle separately, beginning 1 Jul 2003.
A Japanese delegation is also in Canada this week to do a review of
Canada's investigation into the source of the country's only case of
mad cow disease.
The closed U.S. border is costing the Alberta cattle industry 11
million Canadian Dollars a day.
